      <hedline>
        <hl1>To Lead Our Schools</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Letter by Eric Nadelstern, New York City high school principal, says primary aspect of his work is instructional leadership</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''Helping Principals Learn to Use Business Management Skills'' (Education page, June 28):</p>
        <p>While it is true that public school principals must be effective managers, the primary aspect of this work is instructional leadership. School leaders who model successful educational practices have a profound influence on what teachers do with students in the classroom.</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''Helping Principals Learn to Use Business Management Skills'' (Education page, June 28):</p>
        <p>While it is true that public school principals must be effective managers, the primary aspect of this work is instructional leadership. School leaders who model successful educational practices have a profound influence on what teachers do with students in the classroom.</p>
        <p>Public schools will not improve until we decide to select principals from among our best teachers.</p>
        <p>ERIC NADELSTERN  Long Island City, Queens  June 28, 2000</p>
        <p>The writer is a New York City high school principal.</p>
      </block>
